Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass:**

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

**Key points:**

| Detail | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Save in **`OnStopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **`OnDestroying`** | Android back-button can skip `Stopped` |
| Restore in **`OnResumed`** | Fires when returning from background |
| Use **`Preferences`** | Fast & synchronous — avoids ANR/watchdog kills |
| **Don't** save in `OnDeactivated` | That fires for dialogs/notification shade too — the app may never actually background |

> **Tip:** `OnResumed` does *not* fire on first launch (the sequence is `Created` → `Activated`). Load any saved draft in your page's constructor or `OnAppearing` for the initial launch case.
